Perfect! Now I can see the issue. Looking at the test `sameHeadersCombineWithComma()`, it expects that when there are multiple values for the same header, they should be combined with commas. The test creates a header map with multiple values for "Cache-Control" and expects the result to be "no-cache, no-store".

Let me look at the `processResponseHeaders` method to see where the bug is. In the method around line 760, I can see the issue:

```java
} else { // combine same header names with comma: http://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616/rfc2616-sec4.html#sec4.2
    if (!values.isEmpty())
        header(name, values.get(0));
}
```

The comment says "combine same header names with comma", but the code is only taking the first value (`values.get(0)`). It should combine all values with commas.

Let me implement the fix:

